  "prompt": "How exactly does banning Rs 500 and Rs 1000 notes curb the problem of black money?",
  "response": "The demonetization of Rs 500 and Rs 1000 notes in India in 2016 was aimed at curbing black money through several mechanisms:\n\n1. Forcing black money holders to:\n- Deposit unaccounted cash in banks\n- Pay taxes on undeclared income\n- Risk investigation if large cash deposits were made\n\n2. Disrupting:\n- Counterfeit currency circulation\n- Cash-based corruption\n- Underground economy transactions\n\n3. Reducing:\n- Cash-based tax evasion\n- Illegal transactions\n- Funding for illegal activities\n\n4. Pushing towards:\n- Digital/electronic transactions\n- Formal banking systems\n- Greater financial transparency\n\nHowever, the actual effectiveness was debated:\n- Most black money was returned to banks\n- Large economic disruption\n- Significant implementation challenges\n- Limited long-term impact on black money generation\n\nEconomists and experts had mixed opinions about the policy's overall success in addressing black money comprehensively.\n\nThe primary goals were to:\n- Reduce cash in the parallel economy\n- Increase tax compliance\n- Promote digital financial systems\n\nWhile well-intentioned, the practical outcomes were complex and not entirely as anticipated.",
